To verify if you are running an Intel Core Ultra Series 1 (codenamed "Meteor Lake") on your Framework 13, you can use several standard Linux tools.

Since you're on Arch, you likely have these installed, or can quickly grab them from the official repositories.

1. The Quickest Way (Terminal)
Open your terminal and run:

Bash
lscpu | grep "Model name"
What to look for:

Series 1 processors follow the naming convention Intel(R) Core(TM) Ultra [5/7/9] [1xx][H/U].

Example: Intel(R) Core(TM) Ultra 7 155H or Intel(R) Core(TM) Ultra 5 125H.

If you see "12th Gen" or "13th Gen" (e.g., i7-1360P), you are on an older Framework 13 model.

2. Using inxi (More Detailed)
If you want a cleaner, hardware-focused summary, use inxi. If it's not installed, run sudo pacman -S inxi.

Bash
inxi -C
This will output something like:

CPU: 16-core (6-P + 8-E + 2-LPE) Intel Core Ultra 7 155H (-MT-MCP-)

The LPE (Low Power Island) cores are a hallmark of the Core Ultra Series 1 architecture.

3. Visual Verification (Hardware)
If you aren't sure about the software output, you can identify the Series 1 Framework 13 by its physical ports and screen:

The Display: The "Series 1" model often ships with the 2.8k (2880x1920) display, which features distinctive rounded top corners.

Expansion Cards: It supports the newer USB-C expansion cards with improved power delivery, though these look identical to the older ones from the outside.

