To check for the NPU (Neural Processing Unit)—a key feature of the Intel Core Ultra Series 1—you need to look for the Intel VPU (Versatile Processing Unit) device. On Linux, this is handled by the ivpu driver.

1. Check for the Hardware Device
Run the following command to see if the kernel identifies the NPU hardware on the PCI bus:

Bash
lspci -nn | grep -i "VPU"
Expected Output:
You should see a line mentioning an Intel Corporation Device 7d1d (or similar) labeled as a "VPU" or "AI Accelerator."

2. Verify the Kernel Driver (ivpu)
Even if the hardware is there, the NPU requires the ivpu driver to be loaded. Check if it's active:

Bash
lsmod | grep ivpu
If the command returns nothing, the driver isn't loaded. On Arch, this usually means you need to ensure your kernel is up to date (6.3+ is required, though as of 2026, you likely have a much newer one).

3. Real-time Monitoring with intel-gpu-tools
The NPU is often grouped with the GPU tools. You can use intel_gpu_top (part of the intel-gpu-tools package) to see if the NPU is actually doing work.

Install: sudo pacman -S intel-gpu-tools

Run: sudo intel_gpu_top

What to look for:
In the dashboard that appears, look for a section labeled "Video/Enhancement" or specifically "NPU". If the NPU is detected, it will appear as a separate engine block below the 3D/Render engines.

4. Direct Kernel Logs (Dmesg)
If you suspect it’s not working, check the boot logs to see if the firmware failed to load:

Bash
sudo dmesg | grep -i ivpu
Note: If you see "firmware: failed to load intel/vpu/vpu_37xx_v0.0.bin", you may need to install the linux-firmware package or ensure your /lib/firmware/intel/vpu/ directory is populated.

Summary Checklist
Kernel Version: Must be 6.3 or higher (check with uname -r).

Firmware: linux-firmware package must be installed.

Device ID: Should be 7d1d for Ultra Series 1.

