Success! Your NPU is physically detected. The ID [8086:7d1d] confirms you are indeed on the Intel Core Ultra Series 1 (Meteor Lake) architecture.

The reason it didn't show up before is likely because your local PCI ID database (which maps those numbers to names) wasn't updated, but the hardware is definitely there.

To actually use it for AI tasks (like background blur in video calls or running Local LLMs), you need to set up the user-space driver and the OpenVINO toolkit. On Arch, the easiest way is via the AUR.

1. Install the User-Space Driver
You need the intel-npu-level-zero driver to allow applications to talk to that hardware.

Bash
# Using an AUR helper like yay
yay -S intel-npu-level-zero-bin
2. Verify the Driver is Active
Once installed, check if the kernel has created the acceleration device node:

Bash
ls -l /dev/accel/accel0
If it exists: The driver is loaded and the hardware is ready.

If it doesn't: You may need to reboot or run sudo modprobe ivpu.

3. Test with npu-top (The "Task Manager" for your NPU)
Just like top for your CPU, there is a utility to see NPU utilization.

Install intel-npu-top-git from the AUR.

Run it: sudo intel-npu-top

4. Setting Permissions
By default, you might need sudo to access the NPU. To allow your user account to use it without root:

Bash
sudo usermod -aG render $USER
(Note: You'll need to log out and back in for this to take effect.)

